Die Ehe Der Maria Braun (The Marriage Of Maria Braun) is one of the most magnificent pieces of German cinema and quite possibly Rainer Werner Fassbinder's finest work. It follows Maria as she attempts to build a life after the war after losing her husband to it a day into their marriage. A remarkable film and performance by Hanna Schygulla where the struggle of building up a life after the war is just as important as how impressively Maria builds it up to the prosperity which she is convinced she requires.  Showing tonight at @britishfilminstitute as part of their Fassbinder season, the screening is followed by a Q&A with Hanna Schygulla; living legend and forever marked as Fassbinder's muse.  #cinema #film #movies #bfi #southbank #fdr #ddr #hannaschygulla #rwfassbinder #fassbinder #rainerwernerfassbinder #london #screening #specialscreening #german #germancinema #germanfilm #dieehedermariabraun #themarriageofmariabraun #angstessenseeleauf #feareatsthesoul

If you love Palestinian food this one can't be missed. My beautiful friend who is also a fantastic Palestinian chef @bandora_cuisine made these beautiful malfouf. Malfouf is middle eastern cabbage that has been pre boiled to soften, then stuffed with minced lamb and rice. It is seasoned as per each family's way. Mine is with garlic and caraway with lots of lemon. They are slow cooked and eaten quickly. This recipe is in my book. You will love it and love Hind too. Lets talk equipment  Every serious lifter needs to invest in some lifting equipment to enchance his or her lifting.  Also getting new shiny toys to play with at the gym is always fun.  These 6 items here arw what I would call essential.  Left to right top row.  1.Liquid chalk. Helping you grip the barbell during those high rep and set workouts. Reduces sweat and makes lifting heavy shit better. 2. Knee sleeves. A good pair of knee sleeves will keep your knees warm and snug. Making more aware of their possition aswell as reducing any aches and pains from multiple squat sessions. 3. Weightlifting shoes. Eleveated heels are a must in most people. Having that few inches can make a huge difference in your squat and stability. 4. Flat shoes. Keeps you close to the ground grips tight and can be used for squats.  5. Belt. A solid belt is an investment that will last you man years if taken care of. Helps you brace your core and easily adds pounds to your lifts. 6. Deadlift socks.  Protecting your shins is essential especially when pulling heavy weights. Public Image Limited, London, England circa 1978. Or should I say more pragmatically, the wo constant members for the first give years or so of PiL. Left: vocalist/ lyricist John Lydon aka 'Johnny Rotten' (ex-Pistol) and: guitarist/ keyboardist Keith Levene (ex-London SS and the Clash). The first two PiL albums, 'First Issue' & 'Second Edition' (aka 'Metal Box') were, and still are, remarkable and virtually indispensable pieces of post-modern 'sturm under drang'. Both were forays into dub, space, clearly 'Krautrock'-influenced and texturally fascinating: shard-like guitar slabs layered over sonorous bottom-end bass and clattering metallic drums. And that was just account opener 'Theme'! An extraordinary and brave move sonically speaking, considering that Lydon had that awful 'voice-of-a-generation' safety pin of Damocles hanging above his brittle but brilliant, multi - hued head.... PiL would never come close to recording another album to turn this magnificent diptych into a triumphal triptych, although 1985's 'Album' came mighty close... For so many years I tried to do business like I was taught "successful people do." I would give it everything I had, and burn out, or never actually get the results I was promised. So many entrepreneurs in my field are able to show up with a kind of consistency that I always found so challenging. Mostly because my energy just flows differently than that. Inspiration is what fuels me, so showing up and sharing when I am not inspired, feels forced and inauthentic, and I've always chosen authenticity above consistency. Things have to FEEL GOOD to me in order to make sense. Otherwise, no thank you. BUT, a huge JOY ROBBER has been the fact that I have misunderstood the way I am designed, thus trying to force myself to  be something I am not. I have taken the last few weeks to go within. EVERYTHING has been up for review and re-evaluation. And in this deep process, insight and information have been revealed to me. So now, I am in a phase of exploration, curiosity, and eagerness as I begin to practice showing up in ways that truly align with how I am designed and to see what happens as a result! We're now seeing the last of the French truffles this season. I'm told there is one 'truffle dealer' who always harvests the last truffles in France every year. They come from one particular site in Provence and chefs who have access to them like to see the skeptical look they get when diners don't believe they are eating French truffles in April. . I like that chefs can be more creative with black truffles, their Alba cousins cannot be cooked and provide no textural sensation. For me the best dishes of the season were: . 3rd. Epicure. Whole Perigord truffle cooked with underbush aromas and Jerusalem artichoke mousseline. Pristine quality truffle with excellent texture (slightly firmer than l'ambroisie). Great theatre too with the fantastic service team cutting open the salt crust to reveal the cooked black diamond (swipe for more photos). . 2nd. Hedone. Perigord truffle omelette. A very thin duck egg omelette almost like a pancake is made from batter containing truffle. Filled with nuggets and shavings of truffle along with smoked potato and celeriac mousseline, and served with raw truffle shavings and a truffle sauce/purÃ©e. A dish showcasing all the different flavours and textures of truffle. Absolutely dazzling. . 1st. L'ambroisie. A historical dish that needs no introduction so I won't elaborate other than to say eating this with Chateau Rayas is one of the most blissful dining moments I have had. It's always perfect. . Bravo Eric, Mikael and Bernard!!

He paid the ultimate sacrifice so we could be here today. My thoughts go to those who are attending on behalf of Devon and Cornwall police and each and every one of them represents us all up there in London today. Rest easy PC Palmer, you can stand down. "To some this is just a blue line, to others it's a family crest" "The Final Inspection"  The policeman stood and faced his God, Which must always come to pass. He hoped his shoes were shining. Just as brightly as his brass. "Step forward now, policeman. How shall I deal with you?  Have you always turned the other cheek? To My church have you been true?" The policeman squared his shoulders and said, "No, Lord, I guess I ain't, Because those of us who carry badges can't always be a saint.  I've had to work most Sundays, and at times my talk was rough, and sometimes I've been violent, Because the streets are awfully tough.  But I never took a penny, That wasn't mine to keep.... Though I worked a lot of overtime When the bills got just too steep.  And I never passed a cry for help, Though at times I shook with fear. And sometimes, God forgive me, I've wept unmanly tears.  I know I don't deserve a place Among the people here. They never wanted me around Except to calm their fear.  If you've a place for me here, Lord, It needn't be so grand. I never expected or had too much, But if you don't.....I'll understand.  There was silence all around the throne Where the saints had often trod. As the policeman waited quietly, For the judgment of his God. "Step forward now, policeman, You've borne your burdens well. Come walk a beat on Heaven's streets, You've done your time in hell." Or start that business? ___ Living without acting on that can be crippling, and I know that feeling all too well. But what would happen if we listened to that voice? If we took action and wrote that book, or launched that website, or started that business? ___ So here it is. The launch of my site. theavantgardecollective.com The Avant Garde Collective is a travel and lifestyle website showcasing cities around the world and their best people, places, and products. There will be chats with locals, curated city guides, and a look at the goodies created and produced in each city. Oh, and playlists every week! ___ I am by no means an expert. Iâ€™m just a girl who loves people and travel and wants to share that with the world. This is my attempt at beginning to dismantle that pesky resistance. Maybe no one will visit my site, or maybe everyone in the world will, but I invite you to come along for the ride. ___ Sitting back in fear doesnâ€™t get you anywhere and Iâ€™ve sat back for far too long, primarily due to fear. But now is the time to take action and use that courage that I know is in me. In each of us. ___ Link in bio. ___ Come chat with me on instagram at @theavantgardecollective and leave your stories of courage. â €â €â €â €â €â €â € ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ Photo: @steven.a.russell ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ _______________________________________ Good Monday morning from the ancient Roman Baths in Bath, England! Did you have a smashing weekend? I heard recently the Green Party in England is proposing a three-day weekend. Guys, this would be perfect. Monday could suddenly become the day we all get together and travel around in a mini-bus across Britain! Provided: Unlimited happiness, scones and flasks of hot tea. Interested? Let me know below. I'm quite serious. I never joke around when it comes to tea and scones. First stop after landing in London would be a drive over to Bath and to this glorious place (@theromanbaths) - These amazing hot springs were discovered over 10,000 years ago, with the first shrine at this site built by the Celts who dedicated it to the goddess Sulis. When the Romans invaded Britain they constructed a giant temple around 60-70 AD. My favourite part is being able to see the ancient stones used from the temple and even stepping over (via a walkway) the actual path people used many thousands of years ago. It would be lovely to take a dip right here, but sadly that's not allowed but you can take a sip of the water nearby. It's said you will gain eternal life and become immediately more attractive to the opposite sex. At least that's what the lady at the well told me. I may have drunk too much wine in the attached restaurant at this point so my memory is a bit fuzzy. Anyway, many things were thrown into the bath during Roman times as offerings to the goddess Sulis Minerva, including over 12,000 Roman coins. This place was a hive of activity in Roman times... a real treat to the legions who left the warmth of the mediterranean and ended up in chilly old England! Truly, a brilliant place to visit. A must-see for first time visitors to Britain. Lovely shot by @steven.a.russell ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ Want your Photos of Britain to be featured? #MondayMazes . Villa Pisani, Stra, Veneto, Italy . . The magnificent maze at Villa Pisani dates from 1721. It is made up of nine concentric circles of tall boxwood hedges and a turret with exterior winding steps, at it's center.  It is bordered on two sides by beautiful wisteria-covered walkways.  Napoleon was once famously lost in the maze. When Hitler and Mussolini met at Villa Pisani, they both refused to even attempt to enter the maze, in case they also got lost! . . . Work life balance  I've asked myself a million times if I have it or  not. Like many of these things it starts as  something we personally decide that then  becomes a thing.  A meaningless label that those around us  can mark us on. Like 'Mum or Dad or  hard worker'. Labels have a habit of stopping us from taking the time to create our own definition which  prevent us from ever achieving 'it'. So instead of the question - do I have 'work  life balance.' I dug a little deeper:  Which relationships are important to me and how would I most like to demonstrate that/ experience them?  How will I know if this is happening?  What is important to me in business and how  will I know if I am moving toward this?  What is important to me in wealth and how  will I know if I am moving towards this?  What adventures do I want to go on this year? (Put them in the diary for the whole year)  What health markers am I working towards?  What daily actions do I hope will move me  towards them?  When will I test and re-evaluate these?  Work life balance is a meaningless term  because we tend to use time as our measure of "success". But being home with the family for 4 hours  while being distracted disengaged and short  fused... Is not the same as being mentally present, enthusiastic and fun.  In the absence of personal definitions we  always revert to cultural norms to measure  our success.  This is the sole cause of stress in our lives.  So why not take the time and define.  It works for me.  Have a great day  Ed

Love all of your edges ğŸ’ƒ . I love to dress up, wear make up and heels and totter about a nice bar with a glass of fizz in hand schmoozing. I also love to wear patterned skinny jeans, a loose tee and air force ones and skank out (dance for the non-London crew) until I forget what time it is in a club with a little bit of dark rum in my system. My wardrobe is beyond varied. But I'm never fake. I know myself (well I feel like now it's more appropriate to say I'm learning and ever becoming myself lol) and I see my multi-faceted lifestyle as one of my greatest strengths. Being a social chameleon means I am just as at ease at a black tie dinner with all that extra cutlery (always start from the outside and politely decline unshelled shellfish) as I am at a rough and ready spot in East. I might now live in Dulwich Village, but I'll always be that girl from Croydon who grew up in a mad house, a series of B&Bs and a hostel. Celebrate your edges. Empire Hookah Lounge 667-669 Green Lane, Dagenham RM8 1YA * Light Snacks, Drinks, Shakes, Mocktails, Shisha * Private booth * Parking free after 18:30 & Sunday __________________________________________________ Location: â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Service: â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Atmosphere: â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Smoke: â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ Value for money: â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸ __________________________________________________  Dagenham, Essex, just on the outskirts of Goodmayes is Empire Hookah lounge. The team here have years experience of serving shisha and providing entertainment.  Upon a friendly arrival we were seated on the most comfortable and lavish seats which we sunk into whilst ordering from a striking selection of flavours and drinks. These arrived very quick, I don't know if it's because it wasn't very busy or just how they roll here but we were already impressed. The smoke was very good, flavour was nice and lasted all night, actually smoked even better after the coal change. These guys know how to make a good shisha belive me. The staff were so pleasant and went the extra mile in actually running out to buy us a deck of cards.  The music was at angood level and with screens scattered around the lounge you can count on Empire to show your favourite team or boxer. They regularly have a inhouse DJ and live performances. Masters of entertainment they are and skilled shisha connoisseurs they remain to be. I would highly recommend this lounge, definitely one of the only ways to go in Essex for a good smoke.  Overall we give Empire Hookah Lounge 9ï¸âƒ£out 10.

At Gatwick airport, London, the businessman  crosses path with hard working citizens of the world for few seconds. During his path, he is immersed in the so believed culture of those individuals with traditional music, noises of waterfalls and insects of the forest. The westerner businessman does not seem to care, barely lifting his head up to take a look at the photographs. This wasn't an attempt to bring them closer, but a strategy for a bank company to sell their services, receive income from the humanity of others. Should we be glad that a majority of us are still appealed by images of hard working people from the other side of the world. Or should we instead by worried that we are losing this humanity to the capitalist cooperations and to our consumption. #photography #travel #London #message #humansofearth #Dubai

If he doesn't see you, look into the water as he is merely reflecting back all the ways you don't see yourself. Don't let him steal your peace.

Artist of the day: I've just been to see David Hockney's exhibition at Tate Britain - what a show! Hockney appeared under the British version of Pop Art, but his work explores many genres including expressionism, photo collage, and computer-aided work. He is best known for his painting work, and is Britain's best known living artist, and probably their best. What a colourful inspiration as my friends in Australia live through Autumn, and those in Britain enjoy the beaming rays of Spring. Enjoying Japan cherry blossom at Fushimi Momoyama Jyo (Castle), Kyoto. This is one of the most beautiful secret place to see and enjoy cherry blossom. Definitely no crowded and you surety will enjoy a wonderful serene moment here, because all the visitors here are local Japanese, almost no tourist will come to here. There are lots of cherry trees in different colors in this castle.  Fushimi Momoyamajyo is one of the eleven wards in the city of Kyoto, in Kyoto Prefecture, Japan. Fushimi Castle, originally built by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, with its rebuilt towers and gold-lined tea-room; and the Teradaya, an inn at which Sakamoto RyÅma was attacked and injured about a year before his assassination. Also of note is the GokÅgu shrine, which houses a stone used in the construction of Fushimi Castle. The water in the shrine is particularly famous and it is recorded as one of Japan's 100 best clear water spots. Kyoto, Japan.

As on this day, bananas were first sold in Britain, at a herbalist shop run by a man called Thomas Johnson. It seems to me, she looked, my way,  then passed me, for another day, and once again, my sun's refrain, hath left me, shivering, in the rain.  To hardness, I must confess, as I succumb, to loneliness, yet every day, I seek the sky, and hope to see,  Love's Ravens fly.  Although, it is a rarity, I hope,  someday, that I might see, a flock, that flies, majestically, of Ravens, flying unto me. ------------------------------------------- Real Historic English Pub FOR SALE! Godfrey's Dream, (Excerpt). ------------------------------------------- Amongst the sleeping, trees that twist, there rose, a fog, a creeping mist, against a sky, of emerald green, the Dragon's breath, possessed the scene, twas never ever, seen before, and all knew, the Dragon, lived no more. Oh! tortured soul, he found release, upon a sword, he came to cease, and as a hero, he had made, with sadness, upon the ground, was laid, The Dragon, who whispered, unto the hero's ear, with tender words said; 'Do not fear, for once, I have expired, my work is done, that God required, The Ring be your, forevermore, yet of the curse, do not ignore', thence whispered he, unto his ear, the secret, that the hero, did hear, before The Dragon, found release, and drifted,  to his final peace. And lo ! as the beast, did retire, his soul rose upward, higher and higher, until he stood, face to face, with God's Angels, In heavens embrace, unto Valhall, The Dragon's final,  resting place. --------------------------------------- Thanet, England, 08.04.2017 ---------------------------------- -------- Real Historic English Pub FOR SALE! Masha Reva || Designer & Illustrator  Masha Reva (@mashareva) is designer and illustrator who graduated in 2015 with an MA from Central Saint Martins (@csm_news). She studied previously in Ukraine, where she is originally from, and her Ukrainian background has influenced a great deal of her work. Her MA project detailed the revolution in Ukraine, and she has gained recognition for her styling a series of photographs by Armen Parsadanov called Drawings on Kyiv kids that capture youth culture in contemporary Ukraine. Shortly before graduating from CSM, Reva received sponsorship from Pepsi (@pepsi) and Vogue Italia (@vogueitalia) for winning their Pulse of New Talent competition, through which she produced two collections.

Now let me start by making something very clear: in no way I'm trying to say you should not go through some form of formal education. It lays the foundation on which we start. Now I do believe there is a lot of room for improvement in our school system, but for 99.99% of the people going through this system is much better than the alternative. What I was trying to say was that formal education is only the start. There are so many ways you can keep learning and educating yourself: Read books, go to seminars, follow online courses, listen to podcasts, etc. And don't wait until you finish your formal education, start as soon as possible! Another thing I truly believe is we should never ever be arrogant and think we cannot learn from someone else who might be much younger or work in a completely different sector. You can always learn, from everyone, I know this from experience. This is what I am currently doing to educate myself: - Taking 2 online courses (Financial trading and Digital Marketing) - Read every day for at least 30 minutes - Listen to audio books whenever I am in the car or taking a walk - Talk regularly to some very talented young people and experienced older entrepreneurs So please invest in yourself, it is probably the best investment you will ever make in your entire life!

"A plan to build a disposal facility for radioactive waste from Chalk River Laboratories near the Ottawa River isn't sitting well with conservationists, but the company behind the project wants to assure people who live by the river the landfill will be safe.  Canadian Nuclear Laboratories has proposed building a five-storey-high mound roughly a kilometre from the river to store mostly low-level waste from the Chalk River nuclear facility, about 180 kilometres west of Ottawa.  The "near surface disposal facility" would be operational by 2020, and would take up to 1 million cubic metres of waste by the year 2070, when it would be closed. "I understand that we definitely need to take care of the waste that's been building up at that site. But of course we have some concerns," Ottawa Riverkeeper Meredith Brown told host Hallie Cotnam on CBC Radio's Ottawa Morning.  Brown is worried about leachate â€” potentially contaminated water coming from the the site â€” seeping in to the river.  But Kurt Kehler, vice-president of decommissioning and waste management at Canadian Nuclear Laboratories, wants to assure concerned residents and environmentalists there's a plan for that. "Leachate occurs while it's being filled. So through precipitation â€” rain and snowfall â€” obviously before it's capped, will get into the waste, and will leach out. And we collect all that leachate and treat it," Kehler said on Ottawa Morning.  Once CNL's contract is up after 10 years, the site and its assets will be the responsibility of the federal government, namely Atomic Energy Canada Limited and the Canadian Nuclear Safety Commission..." #ontario #ottawa #yyz #toronto #mississauga #nuclear #waste #water #river #land #firstnations #environment #hamilton #michigan #lakeerie #lakesuperior #vancouver #canada150 #liberals #government #governmentofcanada #halifax #saskatoon #saskatchewan #london #thunderbay

Please don't get netting on your balcony and if you do already or know someone that has then please remove it as wildlife are at risk of serious injuries. These pigeons were caught in netting with it wrapped around their necks & 3 were already deadğŸ’”Please share! @jj_vegan_jedi  NETS ARE BAD!!!! This was an interesting one this afternoon. London wildlife protection got a photo sent to them by someone passing by regarding pigeons trapped in netting on balcony in N15. We volunteered for this one because we were half an hour away and I have a fold up ladder.  It was assumed that flat was abandoned.  We got there and there was no access to the balcony as you would have to get into another garden first, plus balcony too high for my ladder.  Lucky enough someone was home who's balcony it was. He said he doesn't live there and flat usually empty. I convinced him to let me in and rescue the birds. He let me in and there was pigeon shit piled up so high on the balcony it was like a battery hen farm. 3 dead pigeons amongst the shit, 2 pigeons trapped in netting and one nesting pigeon sitting on eggs! We managed to cut away the mesh from the two pigeons, it took a while and was wrapped around their necks (the fella who lived there, was screaming each time the pigeon moved. He was scared shitless of them hence why they were left there for so long), we then got the pigeons in a box. Picked up the eggs and wrapped them to keep them warm until we get them to Kelly's rescues in Enfield where she has an incubator. The fella who lived there said his uncle was coming to sort out his balcony tomorrow, that's why we took the eggs away from nest. The mum flew off and kept flying back and forward...Heartbreaking to take eggs like this but had to be done. I then destroyed the net and took it away so no more can become trapped in it.  The two pigeons and the eggs are now at Kelly's Rescues. One egg was some distance from the nest and cold so I don't think will hatch. The other two eggs were warm as mum had just been sitting on them so they should stand a good chance at nesting. #wildlife #pigeons #londonwildlife #animalrescue #vegan #vegans #vegansofig #vegansofinstagram #wildliferescue

Joy. ğŸ™ŒğŸ¿ @OurFamilyDinner #London  It is hard to fully express how much faith these photos from #OurFamilyDinner London give me. First, I never thought I would see the day we would have an entire city having pepe soup (outside of Lagos), eating and sniffling together like a family. Most importantly, this photo means so much to us because I know all of what these hosts went through to host this dinner. Hosting for us is not event planning, it's community building and that community building is hard work. It's hard to invite people to a dinner gathering on the premise of hospitality (the love of strangers), when everything around us screams, utility and consumption, the "what do I get out of this?" and "why do I have to be at a dinner with people I don't know." It takes a special person to take on what we believe is a perfect mission alongside imperfect people through an imperfect process. (Me: chief imperfect ğŸ™‹ğŸ¿â€â™‚ï¸) I've witnessed this first hand in London and how in spite of the sea of imperfection, they persevered so that we could have a dinner like this past weekend where ambrosia, aka, Naija Jallof ğŸ‡³ğŸ‡¬ was served to our own. Swipe left and see that brother's face, it was the Jallof.  Our hosts deserve all the praise. Love and gratitude to our international leader, Amy! Special thanks to Crystal, Catherine,Â Â Eki (co-founding host) and Reni (in the middle of the first photo), who was at the first ever Our Family Dinner in NYC before we even knew what it was and now, nearly 10 years later, she persisted through a heavy past six months and gave our family in London a night to remember. This definitely sums up my whole attitude to fitness. ----- So a bit of an update about my health, cause I've had a few questions about it since my Disneyland post.. I've had ME and Fibromylagia for almost 6 years now, and I'm currently the best / healthiest / strongest I've been with it.  I still have to pace myself a lot. I went to three blogging events this week, which meant that I've been unable to go to the gym and I've had to spend the whole day in bed today to recuperate. ( Which was helped by binge watching #13reasonswhy ) ----- When I am well enough to go to the gym I try to avoid impact exercises, and focus on using my body weight. I also struggle to lift weights because my hands and wrists are so weak, so I tend to use machines rather than free weights.  Why is this all important? Because I see exercise as a privilege, not a chore. Every day that I'm able to hit the gym is a damn good day. I might not be able to do box jumps but I can do other things. No workout is a bad workout. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ¼

Hard to believe this is the same mouth, isnt it? There's often no need for expensive dentistry, when a half an hour visit to us can dramatically alter the appearance for the better. We tried our best to make this patient laugh as hard as we could - and took a photo.  Often just naturally plumping out the lips with a little filler isn't enough to make the mouth as perfect as it could be. A gummy smile can make a patient feel self conscious (although we do like the little nuances that make you, you! It's all down to individual choice however). It has been shown that a smile will usually be perceived as gummy when there's 4 mm of gingival show . Many people are not aware that there are options for the correction of this. In seconds we can administer a small amount of Botox which when injected into the levator muscles of the upper lip ( as above ) - can be life changing and give the perfect smile. It prevents these muscles from being hyperactive, so as the lips better cover the gum and even look a lot thicker when you smile.. without the use of filler! Just because the top lip cant be pulled so tightly. These patients don't need filler... just these hyperactive muscles, relaxing. BUT We add filler in some cases too, for the final finishing touch and extra volume- as per this patient.  This is one of our treatments that makes an enormous confidence difference - you can at last teeth smile in photographs with confidence! The procedure takes less than a minute to inject and costs only Â£150 in the northern base and Â£200 in London/Eire! Aparigraha or Non - attachment:  One of the most difficult yoga commandments (yamas). As yoga teachers we preach a lot about the asana, the breath and generally what we teach in our weekly classes.. But we often forget to mention very important parts of yoga such as the yamas and niyamas. Aparigraha is my absolute favourite one to talk about maybe because it's extremely difficult to practice non - attachment. It teaches us that being too attached to people, things or goals only brings more suffering, because we attract negativity through attachment and we create competition, jealousy and separation that way. Simply becoming aware of all that, we can let go of any expectations and just embrace the journey. Practicing non - attachment simply means being able to appreciate what we have achieved today, see what we really need and love unconditionally.

Today(11/April/2017), marks my last day of my Europe Trip.  Visited Amsterdam, the city where there are not bicycles than human beings. Literally everyone owns a bicycle and rides everywhere. Day and night there's people taking weed at every corner of the street. Overall it's my most favorite place in this trip.  Next we went over to Paris, the city of love. One word, beautiful. Many many beautiful architecture and it was a sign to behold. Visited the Eiffel Tower, the Louvre Museum and saw the  actual Mona Lisa painting in there. The apartment we lived in was probably the best part of everything.  Finally London, what can I say, all the hype about London is all so real. It's really a place I quickly felt home. Felt very similar to Singapore but with better culture. I love London and I'll definitely be back !  Thank you @chehoe and @__bingh__ for going thru this amazing trip with me and handling my nonsense. I owe this trip all to you guys. It wouldn't have been the same without the both of you.  This isn't the last of my travels. :) . . #amsterdam #paris #london #reflection #trip #europe #backhome #shotoniphone7plus #towerbridge #toweroflondon

The social enterprise is not only based in Trellick Tower, it is also named after its architect, Erno Goldfinger. He built this infamous structure inspired by Du Corbusier in the 70ies and it became one of the worldwide most outstanding structures in the Brutalist style (coming from beton brut). I chased money for so long I stayed broke!  Llewellyn Davies had to buy me a gym membership , a weekly food shop and support me for several months.  The moment I realised it was never about money and never will be everything changed rapidly.  I CHASED HAPPINESS and started coaching people for FREE because at that moment in time I was sad , lonely and some could say "depressed." (There is no fun eating super noodles all week because they are cheap. ) I offered that much value people would refuse to train with me for free so I started my own fitness company focused on giving tremendous amount of VALUE and MOTIVATION for only Â£10 per hour.  I vowed never to chase money again and i never have.  Am I financially driven ..... YES  BUT I also understand the importance of happiness and doing something you love for long enough until you find yourself in a position to monetise doing it for a living.  I've just booked my 9th holiday for this year to Vietnam and I still hustle with NO LAPTOP or business model.  Self belief goes a long way. So if you think you can't achieve success based on your ability to do something you love for a living your wrongâœ…  I urge you all to continue to struggle and progress along the way because you will look back with a smile on your face. #hustle #hustlehard #mindfulness #mindcoach #grind #millionaire #focus #winning #london #nlp #smile #positivevibes #beyourself #SophisticatedHustlers #Millionairemindset #Personaldevelopment #Focus #Believe #Succeed #Winning #Thinkandgrowrich #Businessowners #Lifecoach #Motivation #positivevibes #Goals #Insta

#BringBackOurGirls! That's the message #Black audience members in the #UK had for #JohnRidley at a screening for his latest project on the #BlackPanther movement in 1970s England. At a #London screening for the project that is set to air later this month on Showtime, viewers questioned why #FridaPinto, an Indian actress, was cast in the lead activist role. Another noted that the only black woman in the project plays an informant. Still, one more screening viewer accused the writers of erasing black women from a movement they were so clearly a part of. One awkward exchange went like this; "...why are there no black women at the forefront of the struggle? That doesn't necessarily accurately reflect what happened in the 70s in the UK." #BabouCeesay, a black UK actor cast in the lead role, attempted to clapback with, "Wow, really? You know this because you read about it?" To which she replied, "No, we know this because our parents were a part of it." Ridley then went on to defend his choice for making the lead protagonists a married, mixed-race couple because, as the son of an interracial relationship who also happens to be in a mixed marriage, he doesn't see his story often reflected in film and television roles. Now, there is an old saying that art imitates life but in the case of a topic like this, shouldn't art also imitate reality? ğŸ“· #ChrisPizzello @InvisionAgency

Beautiful. Sad. Fascinating.  The Crossbones Graveyard/Garden is a post-medieval un-consecrated pauperâ€™s burial ground with the remains of an estimated 15,000 people buried there. A dig in 1992 uncovered 148 graves, dating from between 1800 and 1853. Over one third of the bodies were perinatal (between 22 weeks gestation and seven days after birth). A further eleven percent were under one year old. The adults were mostly women aged 36 years and older.  The graveyard gates have been decorated with messages, ribbons and flowers as a voluntary act of remembrance by visitors to the site over the years, and forms a key element to the identity of the site. The garden is kept by local volunteers, showing respect to the dead who are buried beneath.  The remains of the dead have been carefully coveredÂ and protected. Drystone wall beds have been build and various plants, bushes, wildflowers and trees have been planted in them to create a raised garden. There is also wildlife pond, wardens hut, and artist wood-worker Arthur DeMowbray was commissioned to create the Goosewing Entrance.  #crossbonesgraveyard #london

British-Croatian Society Meet-up at Eclipse on Thursday 27th April from 7pm to 10pm! Come along for a chat about all things Croatian! The intention is for people with any form of interest in Croatia to meet up, socialise and have a chat in an informal atmosphere. Whether you are a Croatian resident in London or someone who has recently visited Croatia for the first time and want to know more, this event is for you. The event is of course open to both members and non-members. It provides an excellent opportunity for anyone to come and meet British-Croatian Society members and even to join and become members if they so wish!  You will also have a chance to meet with HE Ambassador of Croatia Dr Ivan Grdesic who will be attending informally to meet up with us!  We will be meeting at Eclipse 111-113 Walton St, Chelsea, London SW3 2HP from 7pm! We have reserved special separate area for our meet up! BCS member Tihana Borovcak Kovacevic will be there from the start 7pm to meet you all!  Weâ€™ll be there between 7 PM and 10 PM. Mention @andersoncraftales to me and I will break out in a huge smile. I can't say enough about the amazing beer and even better people that are part of this London brewery. Today marks the final post about my week long Polkapolooza tour across Ontario that encompassed 50 breweries, 27 cities and more than 2700 Kilometers. Check the link in my bio for the whoe story of Day 7 which culminated at this brewery... Anderson  Craft Ales was the 50th and final stop on the tour and we had an amazing time. Trust me,  you need to get down there and check it out for yourself. To commemorate that fantastic night,  I am cracking open this 4.6 % #crushable Brown Ale, which was my favourite of the style from 2016. May as well be again this year, spot on for everything. Pours a clear copper with a white head that lingers a bit before fading to the surface. Smells delicious with chocolate and a nutty aroma. On the sip, it is exactly what a brown ale should be. Chocolate, toasted malts  biscuits and a nutty front lead to a dry slight coffee finish. A classic and it's not even a year into the brewery's existence. Big thanks again to Jim, Pat and Aynsley for a night we will.never forget. The Swan Bells, Perth, Western Australia.Â The St Martin-in-the-Fields bells can be traced to before the 14th century. They were recast in the 16th century by order of Queen Elizabeth I and again between 1725 and 1770 by members of the Rudhall family of bell founders from Gloucester. Due to be recast leading up to 1988, instead they were tuned and restored at London's Whitechapel Bell Foundry and donated to Western Australia, on the initiative of local bellringer and businessman Laith Reynolds. They are rare in that they are one of the few sets of royal bells, and more so since they are the only set known to have left England. The bells are also known to have rung as the explorer James Cook set sail on the voyage that founded Australia.
